## 5. Market Analysis

- **Industry size and trends:** The U.S. Demolition & Wrecking industry is roughly $11.2B in 2026, having grown at a ~5.1% CAGR over 2020–2025 (IBISWorld). The broader Construction & Demolition (C&D) waste management market grew from ~$216B (2025) to ~$233B (2026), a ~7.5% CAGR, driven by sustainability mandates and urban redevelopment. U.S. C&D recycling rates are estimated near 76%.
- **Growth drivers and barriers:** Drivers — urban redevelopment, tenant-improvement churn in commercial real estate, school and infrastructure renovation cycles, and rising landfill-diversion/recycling requirements. Barriers — fuel and subcontracted-labor cost inflation has compressed demolition-contractor profits; revenue is project-cyclical and tied to commercial construction activity.
- **Competitive landscape (Denver demolition peers):**
  - Superior Demolition, Inc. — Denver commercial interior/exterior demolition since 1997; established competitor.
  - Gorilla Demolition (Englewood) — woman-owned, 15+ years, selective interior to full building; clients include Denver International Airport.
  - American Demolition, Inc. — 1,000+ Colorado demolition projects, large-scale structural demolition.
  - Construction-sector M&A comps: specialty/heavy construction transacts at roughly 2.0x–4.1x EBITDA and ~2.2x–2.9x SDE — the subject's 5.48x ask sits clearly above market.

